{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Generation",
      "simpleDefinition": "The process of producing electricity from various energy sources before it is sent to the grid.",
      "anchor": "The starting point of the electrical supply chain.",
      "misconception": "Thinking generation only happens in massive power stations; it also includes small-scale micro-generation."
    },
    {
      "term": "Transmission Voltages",
      "simpleDefinition": "The specific high-voltage levels used to move electricity efficiently over long distances across the UK.",
      "anchor": "The 'motorway' of the electrical system, operating at 132kV, 275kV, or 400kV.",
      "misconception": "Believing any high voltage is a transmission voltage; in the UK, this term specifically refers only to 132kV, 275kV, and 400kV."
    },
    {
      "term": "Micro-generation",
      "simpleDefinition": "Small-scale production of electricity, usually by individual households or small businesses.",
      "anchor": "Local power produced exactly where it is needed, like a single wind turbine on a farm.",
      "misconception": "Assuming all electricity must come from the National Grid."
    },
    {
      "term": "Photovoltaic",
      "simpleDefinition": "A method of generating electricity by converting sunlight directly into electrical energy.",
      "anchor": "Solar panels found on domestic rooftops.",
      "misconception": "Confusing solar PV (which makes electricity) with solar thermal (which only heats water)."
    },
    {
      "term": "Biomass",
      "simpleDefinition": "An energy source derived from organic materials, such as wood pellets or plant waste, which is burned to generate power.",
      "anchor": "Fuel made from recently living organic matter.",
      "misconception": "Thinking biomass is a fossil fuel because it is burned; biomass is considered renewable because the fuel can be regrown."
    },
    {
      "term": "kV (Kilovolt)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A unit of measurement equal to 1,000 volts.",
      "anchor": "1 kV = 1,000 Volts.",
      "misconception": "Forgetting the 'k' multiplier, which leads to underestimating the extreme danger of transmission-level pressures."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "The starting point of the supply chain",
    "The motorway of the electrical system",
    "400 kV, 275 kV, and 132 kV",
    "Small-scale local power",
    "1 kV equals 1,000 Volts"
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "33 kV is a transmission voltage",
    "Generation only happens in large power stations",
    "Solar PV and solar thermal are the same thing",
    "Fossil fuels and biomass are the same category"
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "key": "203-5a-teach-check-1",
      "title": "Generation Methods",
      "objective": "Identify the diverse range of generation methods used for electricity distribution.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Electricity generation is the starting point of the supply chain. It involves converting different forms of energy into electrical power before it is sent to the grid. To understand the system, you must be able to identify the various sources used in the UK.",
        "Traditional large-scale methods include burning fossil fuels like coal, oil, and gas, or using nuclear reactors to produce heat for steam turbines. These plants are usually located far from cities and produce massive amounts of power.",
        "Renewable sources are also a major part of the mix. These include wind turbines, wave power, and hydro-electric schemes. Photovoltaic (PV) systems convert sunlight directly into electricity, while biomass involves burning organic materials like wood pellets or plant waste.",
        "It is a common misconception that generation only happens in massive power stations. Micro-generation allows for small-scale local power production, such as a single wind turbine on a farm or solar panels on a domestic roof. Whether it is a massive nuclear plant or a small PV array, these are all valid methods used to feed the distribution network."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about both traditional fossil fuels and modern renewable sources like wind, wave, and photovoltaic systems."
    },
    {
      "key": "203-5a-teach-check-2",
      "title": "Transmission Voltages",
      "objective": "Identify the specific high voltages used in the UK transmission network.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Once electricity is generated, it must be moved across the country to where it is needed. This is the transmission stage, which acts as the 'motorway' of the electrical system. To move power efficiently over long distances with minimal energy loss, we use very high pressures.",
        "In the UK, there are three specific high-voltage levels used for transmission: 400 kV, 275 kV, and 132 kV. The unit 'kV' stands for kilovolt, where 1 kV equals 1,000 Volts. This means a 400 kV line is operating at a massive 400,000 Volts.",
        "As an electrician, you must be technically precise with these figures. A common mistake is believing that any high voltage counts as a transmission voltage. However, in the UK, the term 'transmission' refers strictly to 132 kV, 275 kV, and 400 kV.",
        "Lower voltages, such as 33 kV or 11 kV, are used later in the journey for local distribution. For this stage of the supply chain, focus only on the three primary transmission levels that move bulk power from the generators to the regional substations."
      ],
      "hint": "Remember the three specific UK transmission levels: 132 kV, 275 kV, and 400 kV."
    }
  ]
}

